### 9. Session and User Type Inference (`auth.$Infer.Session`)

better-auth provides a type inference pattern through `auth.$Infer` that lets you derive TypeScript types from your auth configuration. This is especially useful so you do not have to manually define Session/User types:

**Exporting types from your auth config (`auth.ts`):**

```typescript
import { betterAuth } from "better-auth";
import Database from "bun:sqlite";

export const auth = betterAuth({
  database: new Database("./sqlite.db"),
  emailAndPassword: { enabled: true },
  socialProviders: {
    google: {
      clientId: process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID!,
      clientSecret: process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET!,
    },
    github: {
      clientId: process.env.GITHUB_CLIENT_ID!,
      clientSecret: process.env.GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET!,
    },
  },
});

// Infer types from your auth configuration
type Session = typeof auth.$Infer.Session;

// This gives you:
// Session.session - the session record type
// Session.user - the user record type

// You can also extract them individually:
type User = typeof auth.$Infer.Session.user;
type SessionData = typeof auth.$Infer.Session.session;
```

**Using inferred types in your application:**

```typescript
import type { auth } from "./auth";

// Infer session type from auth instance
type Session = typeof auth.$Infer.Session;

// Use in function signatures
function getUserDisplayName(session: Session): string {
  return session.user.name;
}

// Use in React components
interface DashboardProps {
  session: Session;
}

function Dashboard({ session }: DashboardProps) {
  const user: typeof auth.$Infer.Session.user = session.user;
  return <h1>Welcome, {user.name}</h1>;
}
```

If you use plugins that extend the user or session schema, `$Infer` will automatically include those extended fields.

