### 10. Configuring `trustedOrigins` for CORS

The `trustedOrigins` option tells better-auth which origins are allowed to make cross-origin requests. This is critical in a monorepo where your frontend and API run on different ports during development:

```typescript
import { betterAuth } from "better-auth";
import Database from "bun:sqlite";

export const auth = betterAuth({
  database: new Database("./sqlite.db"),
  emailAndPassword: { enabled: true },

  // Allow requests from your frontend
  trustedOrigins: [
    "http://localhost:5173",    // Vite dev server
    "https://yourdomain.com",   // Production frontend
  ],
});
```

Without `trustedOrigins`, cross-origin requests from your React frontend (running on Vite at port 5173) to your API (running on port 3000) will be rejected. better-auth uses this to set the appropriate CORS headers and validate the `Origin` header on incoming requests.

You can also use a function for dynamic origin validation:

```typescript
export const auth = betterAuth({
  database: new Database("./sqlite.db"),
  trustedOrigins: (origin) => {
    // Allow all localhost ports in development
    if (origin.startsWith("http://localhost:")) return true;
    // Allow specific production domains
    if (origin === "https://yourdomain.com") return true;
    return false;
  },
});
```

