### 1. Creating a Typed Implementer with Context: `implement(contract).$context<AppContext>()`

The `implement` function accepts a contract and returns an `Implementer` object. The `$context<T>()` method sets the initial context type that all procedures in this router will require.

**Key type signatures** (from `/Users/marc/conductor/workspaces/gazed/santiago/node_modules/.bun/@orpc+server@1.13.5/node_modules/@orpc/server/dist/index.d.ts`, lines 744-759):

```typescript
type Implementer<TContract, TInitialContext, TCurrentContext> = {
  $context<U extends Context>(): Implementer<TContract, U & Record<never, never>, U>;
  $config(config: BuilderConfig): Implementer<TContract, TInitialContext, TCurrentContext>;
} & ImplementerInternal<TContract, TInitialContext, TCurrentContext>;

declare function implement<T extends AnyContractRouter, TContext extends Context = Record<never, never>>(
  contract: T,
  config?: BuilderConfig
): Implementer<T, TContext, TContext>;
```

Where `Context` is defined as (from `server.qKsRrdxW.d.ts`, line 5):

```typescript
type Context = Record<PropertyKey, any>;
```

**Usage pattern:**

```typescript
import { implement } from "@orpc/server";
import { contract } from "@repo/api-routes";

// Define your app context type
interface AppContext {
  request: Request;
  // user may or may not be present initially
}

// Create the implementer, typed to require AppContext
const os = implement(contract).$context<AppContext>();
